<p>
<p>An occupational and organizational psychologist is interested in the relationship between the degree of attachment to the company (interval scale) and the number of days of illness in a year. In a random sample of 30 employees, she finds a correlation of <span class="math inline">\(r = .37\)</span>.</p>
<p>What is the null hypothesis when the presence of a correlation is tested?</p>
</p>]]></text>
</questiontext>
<generalfeedback format="html">
<text><![CDATA[<p>
<p>A hypothesis is a statement about the value in the population (<span class="math inline">\(\rho\)</span>). A null hypothesis always states that there is no correlation: (<span class="math inline">\(\rho=0\)</span>).</p>
</p>]]></text>
</generalfeedback>
<penalty>0</penalty>
<defaultgrade>1</defaultgrade>
<shuffleanswers>false</shuffleanswers>
<single>true</single>
<answernumbering>abc</answernumbering>
<answer fraction="0" format="html">
<text><![CDATA[<p>
<span class="math inline">\(H_0: r = 0\)</span>
</p>]]></text>
<feedback format="html">
<text><![CDATA[<p>
A hypothesis is a statement about the value in the population and not in the sample.
</p>]]></text>
</feedback>
</answer>
<answer fraction="0" format="html">
<text><![CDATA[<p>
<span class="math inline">\(H_0: r &gt; 0\)</span>
</p>]]></text>
<feedback format="html">
<text><![CDATA[<p>
A hypothesis is a statement about the value in the population and not in the sample.
</p>]]></text>
</feedback>
</answer>
<answer fraction="100" format="html">
<text><![CDATA[<p>
<span class="math inline">\(H_0: \rho = 0\)</span>
</p>]]></text>
<feedback format="html">
<text><![CDATA[<p>
This is the correct null hypothesis.
</p>]]></text>
</feedback>
</answer>
<answer fraction="0" format="html">
<text><![CDATA[<p>
<span class="math inline">\(H_0: \rho &gt; 0\)</span>
</p>]]></text>
<feedback format="html">
<text><![CDATA[<p>
A null hypothesis always states that there is no correlation.
</p>]]></text>
</feedback>
</answer>
